If two or more couples have an equal majority for the same position,
the following are used to determine placement:
a) If such majorities are equal, then the lowest total (i.e., sum) of
marks given by those judges who form the majority shall
determine the allocation of the place in question.
b) If the totals of marks are also equal, then the next lower place
(or places, as necessary) must be included to break the tie,
with the largest majority of placements being allocated the
The process continues, moving back and forth between Rule 7a
(lowest total) and Rule 7b (largest majority of next lower
placements), until the tie is broken.  If couples are still tied after all
marks considered, then the couples are deemed tied for the event.
If no couple receives a majority of “1st place” marks, then the winner
is the couple who was placed “2nd and higher” by a majority of
judges.  If no couple receives a majority of “1st and 2nd place) marks,
then 3rd place (and if necessary, lower places) must be included
(subject to Rules 6 and 7) to determine placement. The other places
should be tabulated in a similar way.
Test your proficiency for scoring single-dance events.
When all the dances in a multi-dance event have been concluded,
the “placement” order tabulated for each dance is carried to another
sheet showing the places achieved by each couple in each dance.
The 1st place couple in each dance is given a “1,” the 2nd place
couple a “2,” and so on.  The place marks received by each couple are
added together, and the couple with the lowest total is awarded 1st
place.  The couple with the next lowest total is awarded 2nd place,
the next lower total is awarded 3rd place, and so on.
If there is a tie for a place in the final summary, the following are used to break the tie:

column2: If more than two couples tie for 2nd place under Rule 9, 2nd place is awarded to

column1: the couple who has the most “2nd and higher” marks. If the couples have the
same number of “2nd and higher” marks, then the “2nd and higher” marks are
added together and the couple with the lower total is awarded 2nd place (see
Rule 10b).  Still only considering the remaining “tied” couples, 3rd place is
awarded to the couple who has the most “3rd and higher” marks. If the couples
have the same number of “3rd and higher” marks, then the “3rd and higher”
marks are added together and the couple with the lower total is placed 3rd.  This
process continues until all “tied” couples have been awarded placements.

There will be a tie under Rule 10 if any of the following occur. Rule 11 is then

column1: applied to break the tie, but only for the couples actually concerned in the tie:
1.  If the tied couples have won the same number of dances.
2.  If none of the tied couples has actually won a dance.
3.  If the tied couples have the same number of place marks (or higher)
corresponding the place under review, and the totals of those marks are
also equal.  Do not include the next lower placement to break the tie.
4.  If none of the tied couples has actually won a place mark (or higher)
corresponding to the place under review.
It must be remembered that when two or more couples have the same total in the final
summary, then these couples are actually equal in all-round efficiency.  Where this
occurs, the couple who has obtained the highest efficiency in the greatest number of

If after Rules 9 and 10 have been applied the result is still a tie (see
Rule 10e), the judges’ marks for the “tied” couples over all dances
shall be treated as for an individual dance and tabulated per Rules 5
- 8 to break the tie.  If this still results in a tie, there shall be, at the
discretion of the competition organizers, either a re-dance or the
prizes for the places under review shall be divided.  The following
a) If the tie is for 1st place, an absolute majority of “1st place”
marks to the credit of either of the “tied” couples (4 dances _ 5
judges = 20, or a majority of 11) is awarded 1st place.  If neither
of the “tied” couples obtains an absolute majority of “1st place”
marks, the tie is broken using Rule 8.
b) If the tie is for 2nd place, an absolute majority of “2nd and
higher” marks to the credit of either of the “tied” couples is

c) All other “tied” places (3rd place or lower) are decided on
d) If three (or more) couples tie for a place under Rule 10 (for
